NHANES

2024-04-18

library("dplyr")
library("nhanesA")
library("ggplot2")
library("corrplot")
library("ggcorrplot")

demo15_16 <- nhanes("DEMO_I")
bmx15_16 <- nhanes("BMX_I")
slq15_16 <- nhanes("SLQ_I")
auq15_16 <- nhanes("AUQ_I")

demo_bmx <- merge(demo15_16, bmx15_16, by = "SEQN", all.x = TRUE)
demo_bmx_slq <- merge(demo_bmx, slq15_16, by = "SEQN", all.x = TRUE)
merged_data <- merge(demo_bmx_slq, auq15_16, by = "SEQN", all.x = TRUE)
merged_data[sample(nrow(merged_data), 10), 20:40]
before_select <- merged_data

# 2015-16 doesn't have:
# AUQ490 - Problem with dizziness, lightheadedness
# SLD013 - Sleep hours - weekends
selected_vars <- c("RIAGENDR", "RIDAGEYR", "RIDRETH3", "AUQ054", "AUQ270", "AUQ191", "AUQ250", "SLD012", "SLQ030", "SLQ040", "SLQ050", "SLQ120", "BMXBMI")

selected_data <- merged_data[, selected_vars]
selected <- selected_data

# distribution of ages
table(selected$RIDAGEYR, useNA = "always")
hist(selected$RIDAGEYR)

# distribution of ringing/buzzing
table(selected$AUQ191, useNA = "always")
# Yes         No Don't know       <NA>
# 683       4083          1       5204

aggregate(RIDAGEYR ~ AUQ191, data = selected, FUN = mean, na.rm = TRUE)
#       AUQ191 RIDAGEYR
# 1        Yes 49.52709
# 2         No 43.29047
# 3 Don't know 54.00000


# lowest age of AUQ191 respondents is 20
respondents <- selected[!is.na(selected$AUQ191), ]
min(respondents$RIDAGEYR) # 20

over_20 <- selected[selected$RIDAGEYR >= 20, ]
hist(over_20$RIDAGEYR)

which(duplicated(over_20$SEQN)) # no dups
table(over_20$RIDAGEYR, useNA = "always")
table(over_20$AUQ191, useNA = "always")
aggregate(RIDAGEYR ~ AUQ191, data = over_20, FUN = mean, na.rm = TRUE)

# removing "Don't Know and NA" factors in AUQ191
over_20 <- over_20[over_20$AUQ191 %in% c("Yes", "No"), ]
over_20$AUQ191 <- factor(over_20$AUQ191, levels = c("Yes", "No"))
over_20 <- over_20[!is.na(over_20$AUQ191), ]
table(over_20$AUQ191, useNA = "always")

visualizing age and ringing

ggplot(over_20, aes(x = AUQ191, y = RIDAGEYR, fill = AUQ191)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", shape = 20)

unpaired t-test (ringing ~ age)

# res.ftest <- var.test(RIDAGEYR ~ AUQ191, data = over_20)
# shapiro.test(over_20$RIDAGEYR)

t_test_age <- t.test(over_20$RIDAGEYR ~ over_20$AUQ191, var.equal = FALSE)
t_test_age
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  over_20$RIDAGEYR by over_20$AUQ191
## t = 10.829, df = 934.28, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Yes and group No is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  5.106367 7.366860
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Yes  mean in group No 
##          49.52709          43.29047

unpaired t-test (ringing ~ weekday sleep hrs)

# res.ftest_sleep <- var.test(SLD012 ~ AUQ191, data = over_20)
# shapiro.test(over_20$SLD012)

sleep_yes <- over_20$SLD012[over_20$AUQ191 == "Yes"]
sleep_no <- over_20$SLD012[over_20$AUQ191 == "No"]
t_test_sleep <- t.test(sleep_yes, sleep_no)
print(t_test_sleep)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sleep_yes and sleep_no
## t = 0.64186, df = 865.74, p-value = 0.5211
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.08971252  0.17690415
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  7.659226  7.615630
group_by(over_20, AUQ191) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    mean = mean(SLD012, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd = sd(SLD012, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## # A tibble: 2 × 4

## 1 Yes      683  7.66  1.65
## 2 No      4083  7.62  1.51

chi-squared: tinnitus and gender

cont_table_gender <- table(over_20$RIAGENDR, over_20$AUQ191)
cont_table_gender
##         
##           Yes   No
##   Male    362 1907
##   Female  321 2176
chi_sq_gender <- chisq.test(cont_table_gender)
chi_sq_gender$expected
##         
##              Yes       No
##   Male   325.163 1943.837
##   Female 357.837 2139.163
chi_sq_gender$observed
##         
##           Yes   No
##   Male    362 1907
##   Female  321 2176
print(chi_sq_gender)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  cont_table_gender
## X-squared = 9.047, df = 1, p-value = 0.002631
corrplot(chi_sq_gender$residuals, is.cor = FALSE, cl.pos = "b", cl.length = 5, insig = "blank", method = "circle", addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, title = "Chi-Squared residuals for Gender ~ AUQ191",mar=c(0,0,2,0))

# data:  cont_table_gender
# X-squared = 9.047, df = 1, p-value = 0.002631

chi-squared: tinnitus and sleep disorders

over_20_subset <- subset(over_20, SLQ050 %in% c("Yes", "No"))
over_20_subset$SLQ050 <- droplevels(over_20_subset$SLQ050)

cont_table_sleep <- table(over_20_subset$SLQ050, over_20_subset$AUQ191)
cont_table_sleep
##      
##        Yes   No
##   Yes  298  943
##   No   385 3139
chi_sq_sleep <- chisq.test(cont_table_sleep)
chi_sq_sleep$expected
##      
##           Yes       No
##   Yes 177.881 1063.119
##   No  505.119 3018.881
chi_sq_sleep$observed
##      
##        Yes   No
##   Yes  298  943
##   No   385 3139
print(chi_sq_sleep)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  cont_table_sleep
## X-squared = 126.97, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
table(over_20$SLQ050, useNA = "always")
## 
##        Yes         No Don't know       <NA> 
##       1241       3524          1          0
chi_sq_sleep_residuals <- chi_sq_sleep$residuals
rownames(chi_sq_sleep_residuals) <- c("Trouble sleeping", "No trouble sleeping")
colnames(chi_sq_sleep_residuals) <- c("Ringing", "No ringing")

corrplot(chi_sq_sleep_residuals, is.cor = FALSE, cl.pos = "b", cl.length = 5, insig = "blank", method = "circle", addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, title = "Chi-Squared residuals for SLQ050 ~ AUQ191", mar=c(0,0,2,0))

# data:  cont_table_sleep
# X-squared = 126.97, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
